Don't forget that $10 = 1 volunteer hour!

post_text: WPA Community—with the recent announcement from Davis School District regarding the change to their schedule, we want you to know that we are aware of the situation. Throughout the summer we have planned for multiple contingencies for starting the school year as we know times are uncertain and changing daily. Please know that we are taking the time now to consider the implications of each local decision on our WPA community. We will be meeting as a staff this week and will send out communication regarding the start of our school year to our WPA community early next week. We appreciate your patience as we navigate these unprecedented times. Please take a moment to complete the short survey we will soon be emailing out so we can plan accordingly.

2019-2020 WPA Yearbooks have arrived! To pick up your pre-ordered yearbook, stop by WPA TOMORROW Friday, July 10th between 7am and 12pm. Ms. Newman will be stationed outside the school in the Lot A carpool lane.
- - - - - - -
If you did NOT pre-order a yearbook, we have a limited supply available for purchase in person tomorrow on a first come, first serve basis. Each yearbook will cost $20.
- - - - - - -
You may ask a friend to pick up your yearbook for you.
- - - - - - -
If you are unable to pick up your yearbook tomorrow, the front office will open again on August 3rd and you may stop by then during office hours.
- - - - - - -
If you have any questions regarding yearbook pick up, please reach out to Natalie Newman (nnewman@wasatchpeak.org).

post_text:
I am so excited to announce that our school is participating in the OPEN National Virtual Field Day on May 8th 2020. This virtual field day is sponsored and organized by the OPEN National Trainers who have stepped up to create an amazing event that can help bring our entire community together on May 8th. This virtual field Day is optional, but I encourage you and your family to participate. I am also going to encourage all of our teachers, faculty and staff to participate as well.

It is a free virtual field day and everything you need to participate can be found on my google classroom.

Let's have some fun with this OPEN National Virtual Field Day and bring our school and community together!! Stay Safe and Healthy!! —Ms. Randi

post_text: One of the main tenets of our charter that distinguishes us from local public schools is a focus on Service Learning. At the end of each term we have a Service Learning assembly where students from each homeroom share what projects they completed. This past assembly some service learning projects included: educating the school on recycling, filling out a grant for supplies to build a school garden, reviewing and approving grants, creating a food waste system for the school, and gathering food to donate to the local food bank.

Returning Students:
Every year before we run the general lottery, we give existing students the opportunity to register for the following year. This system is now ready and open to register your student.

Steps to Register
1-Login to Aspire
2- Above your student’s address find the link “Can register for grade ___” and click on it.
3- You should be in the student registration portal. Complete the process as directed.
4- If you have more than one returning student you will need to complete this process for each student.

If you have questions or need further assistance, please contact the front office.

Sibling NEW to WPA?
We give priority lottery spots to students with siblings already attending WPA! In order to make sure your student has one of these spots you will need to login to the lottery and reserve it when it opens on January 6th. We will send out reminders and more specific directions after the holiday break.

post_text: Held every January, National School Choice Week is the world’s largest annual celebration of opportunity in K-12 education. The week is nonpartisan and nonpolitical. The goal is to raise awareness of the different K-12 education options available for children, including traditional public schools, public charter schools, public magnet schools, private schools, and online academies.

post_text:
Why does growth mindset matter?
Students with a growth mindset tend to see struggle as a natural part of getting better at something. When they encounter something they can’t yet do, they increase their effort, try new strategies, and end up learning more. Research shows that a growth mindset predicts increased academic achievement and can help narrow achievement gaps.
Though students with growth mindset view challenge as an important part of learning, it doesn’t mean that students “just need to put their heads down and work harder.” Instead, students with a growth mindset see many ways to grow their abilities. They can recognize when they need help, and seek out new strategies.

Tetons Update Day Three: Hello!

We have been so fortunate with the beautiful weather up here! We might get a little rain tonight, but so far it has been high 60’s/70’s. I don’t think we’ll ever get sick of the gorgeous views—simply stunning!

Hawks: Hawks honed their tracking skills at Phelps Lake.

Weasles: Teamwork can be hard but with communication, cooperation, and concern for the group, you'll have success.

Owls: Today the owls focused on adaptations as they observed fish non-native to Wyoming and walked around Jackson lake.

Bison: Today we were stewards by planting willows next to a creek, participating in team building activities, and helping with lunch dishes.

Foxes: Today the foxes hiked to Taggert Lake and learned about animal and plant adaptation in the GYE.

Wolves: What a fantastic day the wolves has hiking to Taggart Lake.

Otters: The Otters had a great day learning about stewardship as we planted willow trees, visited the National Elk Refuge, and practiced teamwork on the lower challenge course.

Bison: Today we were stewards by planting willows next to a creek, participating in team building activities, and helping with lunch dishes.

Foxes: Today the foxes hiked to Taggert Lake and learned about animal and plant adaptation in the GYE.

Wolves: What a fantastic day the wolves has hiking to Taggart Lake.

Otters: The Otters had a great day learning about stewardship as we planted willow trees, visited the National Elk Refuge, and practiced teamwork on the lower challenge course.

Curiosity is about having an open and active mind. It’s about exploration. Not surprisingly, one of NASA’s Mars rovers is named for this strength. Curiosity puts the brain in a state that makes learning easier, more enjoyable, and longer-lasting.

post_text:
Take it HOME Tuesday.
This month’s Patriot Trait is….
Growth Mindset
Growth mindset is a popular notion in the field of education right now, but it’s commonly misunderstood. It might seem like growth mindset implies that everyone has exactly the same potential in every domain, but that’s not quite true. Instead, growth mindset means everyone’s intellectual ability can always be further developed. Growth mindset is not about telling your students to never give up. A benefit of growth mindset is that it helps you stay motivated to stick it out when things are difficult, but telling students not to quit won't do that alone. You have to (truthfully!) convince kids that their efforts will result in increased ability (because ability can grow!) and remind them that they're learning when something is hard for them to do.
Observing Growth Mindset
Having a growth mindset could involve:
• Taking on new challenges with optimism
• Being able to talk about what you learned

post_text:
Take it HOME Tuesday.
This month’s Patriot Trait is….
Growth Mindset
Having a growth mindset means understanding that intelligence can be developed. A growth mindset is a belief that we can get smarter through hard work and practice. This means that struggling with something difficult doesn’t mean you’re not smart—it’s a chance to grow your intelligence. Growth mindset is all about trying hard, using good strategies, and getting the help you need.
